<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900713-0072</DOCNO><DOCID>900713-0072.</DOCID><HL>   Tax Protester Found Guilty   Of Filing False Statements</HL><DATE>07/13/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   TAXES</CO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Jean R. Canon, one of the firstprotesters to be accused of trying to disrupt the tax systemand harass public officials and others by filing false Form1099 reports, was convicted of all charges against him.   After a half-day, non-jury trial, federal Judge Juan G.Burciaga found Mr. Canon guilty of 17 counts of filing falsestatements and making a false claim against the federalgovernment. The 47-year-old defendant represented himself atthe trial, but didn't testify. He is to be sentenced on Sept.28, according to federal prosecutor David Farnham.</LP><TEXT>   Form 1099s are used to tell the Internal Revenue Serviceabout non-wage payments to others. Undetected false reportsmay cause needless and costly IRS audits of the protesters'targets. The use of phony 1099s in New Mexico and elsewhere,which has led to 65 IRS criminal investigations, was thesubject of a front-page article in The Wall Street Journal inApril.</TEXT></DOC>